WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:08.000
A generated RTL design can pass its functional test and still leave an important production question unresolved. SV-Gap makes that handoff visible.

00:08.000 --> 00:19.000
It preserves the functional result, adds declared design intent and structural evidence, and reports what is answered, failed, or still unknown. This is evidence accounting, not silicon signoff.

00:19.000 --> 00:31.000
On a machine with the open RTL prerequisites already installed, one command creates a complete local evidence profile.

00:31.000 --> 00:41.000
Quickstart uses a clearly labelled, known-unsafe bundled fixture. It validates the workflow; it is not a model result.

00:41.000 --> 01:02.000
The supplied functional oracle accepted the candidate. The configured structural rule did not. The profile then names the failed production question: does this candidate satisfy the declared synchronous reset-release requirement?

01:02.000 --> 01:14.000
Unknowns remain unknown, and the profile says what evidence could resolve them: review, repair, an independent backend, or approved adjudication.

01:14.000 --> 01:25.000
To evaluate your own model or agent, wrap it as one command: prompt on standard input, RTL on standard output. Start with one smoke task, inspect the same profile, then scale to the frozen protocol.

01:25.000 --> 01:30.000
Bring one model output, or one production question your benchmark leaves unanswered.
